Biochar in Data Center Decarbonization

Dr. Seth Kane of the UC Davis Materials Decarbonization and Sustainability Center explains how the physical materials in data centers—not just cooling and compute hardware—drive greenhouse-gas emissions, and how biochar mixed into concrete can lower embodied carbon compared with buying biochar only as carbon credits.

Data-center construction is consuming cement and related materials at a rate projected to roughly triple in the United States by 2027 from 2022 levels, with similar growth globally. Those materials matter for corporate net-zero goals because their emissions are large and fast-growing. They also offer a place to store carbon: tech firms already buy large volumes of biochar for carbon markets, and the talk argues embedding biochar in their own concrete can be more effective than offsets alone.

Biochar is produced by heating biomass—ideally residual sources such as wheat straw or forestry residues—in the absence of oxygen, locking biogenic carbon into a solid that can remain stable for centuries. Concrete combines cement (most of the CO₂ footprint), water, and aggregate. Biochar can partially replace cement (cutting emissions but risking strength if overdone), replace fine aggregate (larger volume potential but more property uncertainty and cost impact), or continue to be purchased only as credits (no structural limit, but credit quality and outsourcing draw skepticism).

Sourcing matters: efficient pyrolysis with minimal fossil-energy inputs is much likelier to deliver real carbon removal than high fossil-fuel process heat. Feedstock choice affects strength, silica content, water absorption, and how much carbon ends up stored—rice-hull versus wood biochars behave differently, and conservative engineering baselines are warranted because construction practice changes slowly.

Lifecycle thinking shows aggregate replacement can track credit prices, while cement replacement can beat credit pricing for the same abatement. At facility scale, high-confidence rice-hull cement replacement might trim on the order of seventeen percent of upfront embodied carbon (mostly from cement); wood-based paths can approach larger reductions at moderate confidence, with steel still dominating remaining embodied emissions until other abatement pathways mature.

Challenges include developing standards, overcoming contractor conservatism, and matching regional feedstock availability—rice is not ubiquitous, so wood or other sources may pencil better when transport dominates. ARPA-E funded early lifecycle work; Google supports ongoing LCA and performance studies. Q&A covers literature spread, hyperscaler interest, strength impacts, and how biochar complements wood construction and future greener cement.
